# read in data frame
df = pd.read_csv("acs2017_census_tract_data.csv")

(2) Remove any observations that having missing data. (3) Encode any string data as integers for now. (4) You have the option of keeping the "county" variable or removing it. Be sure to discuss why you decided to keep/remove this variable.

We do not keep county because county can be an indicator for higher child poverty rates and cause bias towards our model. Unfortunately, poverty lines often correspond to county lines in real terms. Therefore, the justification is as follows: on average lower poverty rates happen in certain counties, thus we can use counties to train the model in such a way where poverty ridden counties are more likely to have a higher child povery rate. Is this begging the question? Yes. We are leading the model to an answer because we have a rough association with county vs child poverty rates. We are eliciting certain answers or responses from the model that we expect.

As a business case, we are trying to predict, by county, what the child poverty rate is. However, my justification is that the county dimension can skew the model because the model can just see what the county is for an instance and make an approximation from there. In other words, in a real world scenario, if we were to not have the county dimension we would still be able to predict with some level of accuracy.

[.5 points] Balance the dataset so that about the same number of instances are within each class. Choose a method for balancing the dataset and explain your reasoning for selecting this method. One option is to choose quantization thresholds for the "ChildPoverty" variable that equally divide the data into four classes. Should balancing of the dataset be done for both the training and testing set? Explain.

Balancing should not be done for both training and testing because balancing the testing takes away "real world" distributions for testing. It's ok to balance in training because it would allow our model to strike a better generalization when it comes to "hypothetical" examples. But when posed with unseen data (which acts as "real world" data), we must keep it as true to nature as we can. In our exercise below, we perform an even split using the qcut (quantile cut) function from pandas on Training. For testing, we use the same bins from our training split and apply them onto our testing split using the cut method - which allows us to customize how to cut our buckets.

[.5 points] Assume you are equally interested in the classification performance for each class in the dataset. Split the dataset into 80% for training and 20% for testing. There is NO NEED to split the data multiple times for this lab.

In the following section, we split the data using an 80/20 rule. Although the class assignment said we need to split using these metrics, I think we should also justify why. We split on 80/20 because the amount of observations we have in the dataset allows us to do so. We have a sizeable amount of instances. We don't have too few where we would need to spli 90/10, and we don't have too large of a set where we can afford to split 70/30. We have roughly that middle ground of number of observations.

  • [ ] (1) vectorized gradient computation
  • [ ] (2) mini-batching
  • [ ] (3) cross entropy loss
  • [ ] (4) proper Glorot initialization, at a minimum. There is no need to use momentum or learning rate reduction (assuming you choose a sufficiently small learning rate). It is recommended to use sigmoids throughout the network, but not required.

#Example adapted from https://github.com/rasbt/python-machine-learning-book/blob/master/code/ch12/ch12.ipynb
#Original Author: Sebastian Raschka
class TwoLayerPerceptronBase(object):
    def __init__(self, n_hidden=30, C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights with small random numbers."""
        W1_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W1_num_elems)
        W1 = W1.reshape(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_) # reshape to be W
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        
        W2_num_elems = (self.n_hidden)*self.n_output_
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W2_num_elems)
        W2 = W2.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, b1, b2
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W1, W2):
        """Compute L2-regularization cost"""
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(np.mean(W1[:, 1:] ** 2) + np.mean(W2[:, 1:] ** 2))
    
    def _cost(self,A3,Y_enc,W1,W2):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A3)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _feedforward(self, X, W1, W2, b1, b2):
        """Compute feedforward step
        -----------
        X : Input layer with original features.
        W1: Weight matrix for input layer -> hidden layer.
        W2: Weight matrix for hidden layer -> output layer.
        ----------
        a1-a3 : activations into layer (or output layer)
        z1-z2 : layer inputs 

        """
        A1 = X.T
        Z1 = W1 @ A1 + b1
        A2 = self._sigmoid(Z1)
        Z2 = W2 @ A2 + b2
        A3 = self._sigmoid(Z2)
        return A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, Z1, Z2, Y_enc, W1, W2):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        V2 = -2*(Y_enc-A3)*A3*(1-A3)
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        _, _, _, _, A3 = self._feedforward(X, self.W1, self.W2, self.b1, self.b2)
        y_pred = np.argmax(A3, axis=0)
        return y_pred

class TLPMiniBatch(TwoLayerPerceptronBase):
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.0, shuffle=True, minibatches=1, **kwds):

        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches
        
        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        """ Learn weights from training data. With mini-batch"""
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W1, self.W2, self.b1, self.b2 = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W1_prev = np.zeros(self.W1.shape)
        rho_W2_prev = np.zeros(self.W2.shape)
        rho_b1_prev = np.zeros(self.b1.shape)
        rho_b2_prev = np.zeros(self.b2.shape)

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []
        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
        # keep track of validation, if given
        # provide tuple of this
        # this tracks the health of validation
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            eta = self.eta / (1 + self.decrease_const*i)

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A1, Z1, A2, Z2, A3 = self._feedforward(X_data[idx],
                                                       self.W1,
                                                       self.W2,
                                                       self.b1,
                                                       self.b2
                                                      )
                
                cost = self._cost(A3,Y_enc[:, idx],self.W1,self.W2)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2 = self._get_gradient(A1=A1, A2=A2, A3=A3, Z1=Z1, Z2=Z2, 
                                                  Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx],
                                                  W1=self.W1,W2=self.W2)
                
                # momentum calculations
                rho_W1, rho_W2 = eta * gradW1, eta * gradW2
                rho_b1, rho_b2 = eta * gradb1, eta * gradb2
                self.W1 -= (rho_W1 + (self.alpha * rho_W1_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.W2 -= (rho_W2 + (self.alpha * rho_W2_prev)) # update with momentum
                self.b1 -= (rho_b1 + (self.alpha * rho_b1_prev))
                self.b2 -= (rho_b2 + (self.alpha * rho_b2_prev))
                rho_W1_prev, rho_W2_prev = rho_W1, rho_W2
                rho_b1_prev, rho_b2_prev = rho_b1, rho_b2


            self.cost_.append(mini_cost)
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            
            # calculate the validation accuracy
            if XY_test is not None:
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            
        return self

class TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(TLPMiniBatch):
    def _cost(self,A3,Y_enc,W1,W2):
        '''Get the objective function value'''
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A3)+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A3))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W1, W2)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A1, A2, A3, Z1, Z2, Y_enc, W1, W2):
        """ Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        """
        # vectorized backpropagation
        # V2 represents the cross entropy calculation (negative log likelihood)
        V2 = (A3-Y_enc) # <- this is only line that changed
        V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        
        gradW2 = V2 @ A2.T
        gradW1 = V1 @ A1.T
        
        gradb2 = np.sum(V2, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        gradb1 = np.sum(V1, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # regularize weights that are not bias terms
        gradW1 += W1 * self.l2_C
        gradW2 += W2 * self.l2_C

        return gradW1, gradW2, gradb1, gradb2

class TLPBetterInitial(TLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):             
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights Glorot and He normalization."""
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden + self.n_features_))
        W1 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden, self.n_features_))

        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        # between 
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden))
        W2 = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden)) 
        
        b1 = np.zeros((self.n_hidden, 1))
        b2 = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        return W1, W2, b1, b2

# print out accuracy results
def print_result(nn,X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test,title="",color="red"):
    print("=================")
    print(title,":")
    yhat = nn.predict(X_train)
    print('Resubstitution acc:',accuracy_score(y_train,yhat))
    
    yhat = nn.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test,yhat)
    print('Validation acc:',accuracy)
    
    print("Precision Score:", precision_score(y_test, yhat, average="weighted"))
    print("Recall Score:", recall_score(y_test, yhat, average="weighted"))
    print("F1 Score:", f1_score(y_test, yhat, average="weighted"))
    print("Model error:", 1 - accuracy)
    
    # calculate confusion matrix and plot
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, yhat)
    cm_disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm, display_labels=[0,1,2,3])
    cm_disp.plot()
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.show()
    
    if hasattr(nn,'val_score_'):
        plt.plot(range(len(nn.val_score_)), nn.val_score_, color=color,label=title)
        plt.ylabel('Validation Accuracy')
    else:
        plt.plot(range(len(nn.score_)), nn.score_, color=color,label=title)
        plt.ylabel('Resub Accuracy')
        
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.grid(True)

Neural Network parameters should not be arbitrary - but it is difficult to correctly choose. For my parameters, I chose a more conservative approach with a low normalization parameter, a low learning rate, and a large amount of epochs. The epoch count doesn't really matter so long as it's at least 100, in my opinion. I chose 500 because my machine could handle that amount without sacrificing too much time.

For the hidden layer and all hidden layers after this, I use a rule-of-thumb approach in where the first hidden layer should be: size of the input layer * (anything between 50% and 75%) + size of the output layer. For my purposes, I choose 2/3 as my value to multiply by my input layer. All proceeding hidden layers (in later sections) will be half of the previous layer.

[1 points] Add support for a third layer in the multi-layer perceptron. In the following sections, much like above with the two layer network, I adapt the code (mostly code from lecture) and modify accordingly to implement a multilayer network. This multilayer network can be modified by the user by modifying values n_layers (number of layers) and n_hidden (a list of the number of hidden neurons per layer). Note: the n_layers should be the same value as the length of n_hidden or else the model will not work.

I note changes I have made to each function I changed. Instead of manually creating a specific class for a 3 layer network, I implemented for loops to iterate through each layer to update the weights and biases. A, Z, W, b, and the resepctive grads of W and b will all be held in a matrix - each will be a matrix of matrices where each inner matrix represents the values at that layer (mostly). Later variables like V (sensitivity, not AdaM) have it reversed where the first index is the last layer in the V matrix, as opposed to, for example, the W matrix which the first index corresponds to the first layer and so on.

class MultiLayerPerceptron():
    def __init__(self, n_layers=3, n_hidden=[50,30], C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None):
        np.random.seed(random_state)
        self.n_layers = n_layers  # new parameter for dynamic neural networks
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """
        Initialize weights with small random numbers.
        Changes made:
            Created empty list to store W and b
            Idea is to be dynamic via n_layers by storing all initialized W and b 
            as a list in each list
            Last W must be configured with the last output number of neurons, 
            hence not part of the loop
        """
        # initialize an empty list to store all initialized weights
        All_W = []
        
        # initialize an empty list to store all initialized biases (should all be 1)
        All_b = []
        
        # initialize first layer W
        W_num_elems = (self.n_features_)*self.n_hidden[0]
        W_first = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W_num_elems)
        W_first = W_first.reshape(self.n_hidden[0], self.n_features_) # reshape to be W
        
        All_W.append(W_first)
        
        # initialize first layer b
        b_first = np.zeros((self.n_hidden[0], 1))
        
        All_b.append(b_first)
        
        # iterate through layers
        for layer in range(self.n_layers - 2):  # -2 because we already have 1st and last layer
            W_num_elems = (self.n_hidden[layer])*self.n_hidden[layer + 1]
            W = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W_num_elems)
            W = W.reshape(self.n_hidden[layer + 1], self.n_hidden[layer]) # reshape to be W
            b = np.zeros((self.n_hidden[layer + 1], 1))
            
            # append W and b
            All_W.append(W)
            All_b.append(b)
        
        # intialize last layer
        W_last_num_elems = (self.n_hidden[-1])*self.n_output_
        W_last = np.random.uniform(-1.0, 1.0, size=W_last_num_elems)
        W_last = W_last.reshape(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden[-1])
        b_last = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        
        All_W.append(W_last)
        All_b.append(b_last)
        
        return All_W, All_b
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W):
        """
        Compute L2-regularization cost
        Changes made:
            For L2, we now need to take the summation of all 
            W now that we have a dynamic network
        """
        
        # iterate through each weight and find sum square
        total_weight = 0
        for weight in W:
            total_weight += np.mean(weight[:, 1:] ** 2)
        
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        return (lambda_/2.0) * np.sqrt(total_weight)
    
    def _cost(self, A_last, Y_enc, W):
        '''
        Get the objective function value
        Changes made:
            Need to pass through W as W can be dynamic 
            depending on size of network
            Renamed A3 to A_last for consistency
        '''
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A_last)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _feedforward(self, X, W, b):
        """Compute feedforward step
        -----------
        X : Input layer with original features.
        
        W: Weight matrix of matrix for all layers
            1st matrix = first layer -> hidden layer1
            2nd matrix = hidden layer1 -> hidden layer2
            ...etc
            
        b: bias matrix of matrix for all layers
            1st matrix = first layer -> hidden layer1
            2nd matrix = hidden layer1 -> hidden layer2
            ...etc
        ----------
        A: Activations matrix by each layer
        Z: Layer inputs matrix by each layer

        """
        # initialize list of A and Z to store each layer A and Z
        A = []
        Z = []
        
        # first layer A - store it
        A_first = X.T
        A.append(A_first)
        
        # iterate through layers
        for layer in range(self.n_layers - 1):  # once again, need to skip the last layer
            # calculate Z
            Z_layer = W[layer] @ A[layer] + b[layer]
            Z.append(Z_layer)
            
            # calculate A
            A_layer = self._sigmoid(Z_layer)
            A.append(A_layer)
        
        
        # last layer Z
        Z_last = W[self.n_layers - 1] @ A[self.n_layers - 1] + b[self.n_layers - 1]
        Z.append(Z_last)
        
        # last layer A
        A_last = self._sigmoid(Z_last)
        A.append(A_last)
        
        return A, Z
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A, Z, Y_enc, W):
        """
        Compute gradient step using backpropagation
        Changes made:
            Added V, which is the master list of all V to store
            Added grad_w, which is the master list of all grad for w to store
            Added grad_b, which is the master list of all grade for b to store
        """
        # initialize master lists
        V = []
        grad_W = []
        grad_b = []
        
        # calculate the last layer V, W, b
        V_last = -2*(Y_enc-A[-1])*A[-1]*(1-A[-1])
        gradW_last = V_last @ A[-2].T
        gradb_last = np.sum(V_last, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # append last V, W, b
        V.append(V_last)
        grad_W.append(gradW_last)
        grad_b.append(gradb_last)
        
        # iterate through layers
        # need to reverse because it back propogates
        # also need to go from last layer to 1st layer (0 isn't a layer)
        for layer in reversed(range(1, self.n_layers)):
            V_idx = abs(layer - self.n_layers + 1)

            # update V
            V_layer = A[layer] * (1 - A[layer]) * (W[layer].T @ V[V_idx])
            V.append(V_layer)
            
            # update W
            gradW_layer = V[V_idx + 1] @ A[layer-1].T
            
            # regularize weights that are not bias terms
            gradW_layer += W[layer-1] * self.l2_C
            grad_W.insert(0, gradW_layer)
            
            # update b
            gradb_layer = np.sum(V[V_idx + 1], axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
            grad_b.insert(0, gradb_layer)

        return grad_W, grad_b
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        A, Z = self._feedforward(X, self.W, self.b)
        y_pred = np.argmax(A[self.n_layers], axis=0)
        return y_pred

class MLPMiniBatch(MultiLayerPerceptron):
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.0, decrease_const=0.0, shuffle=True, minibatches=1, **kwds):

        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches
        
        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        """ Learn weights from training data. With mini-batch"""
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W, self.b = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W = []
        rho_W_prev = []
        rho_b = []
        rho_b_prev = []
        
        # iterate through layers and initialize momentum
        for layer in range(self.n_layers):
            rho_W.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            rho_W_prev.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            rho_b.append(np.zeros(self.b[layer].shape))
            rho_b_prev.append(np.zeros(self.b[layer].shape))

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []
        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
        # keep track of validation, if given
        # provide tuple of this
        # this tracks the health of validation
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            eta = self.eta / (1 + self.decrease_const*i)

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward - changed here because function changed in inherited class
                A, Z = self._feedforward(X_data[idx], self.W, self.b)
                
                # calculate cose - changed here because function changed above
                cost = self._cost(A[-1],Y_enc[:, idx], self.W)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                grad_W, grad_b = self._get_gradient(A=A, Z=Z, Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx], W=self.W)
                
                # iterate through the network
                for layer in range(self.n_layers):

                    # momentum calculations
                    rho_W[layer] = eta * grad_W[layer]
                    rho_b[layer] = eta * grad_b[layer]      
                    self.W[layer] -= (rho_W[layer] + (self.alpha * rho_W_prev[layer])) # update with momentum
                    self.b[layer] -= (rho_b[layer] + (self.alpha * rho_b_prev[layer]))
                    rho_W_prev[layer] = rho_W[layer]
                    rho_b_prev[layer] = rho_b[layer]

            self.cost_.append(mini_cost)
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            
            # calculate the validation accuracy
            if XY_test is not None:
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            
        return self

Note: below parameters include 2 hidden neuron parameters. Following my rule, I take 2/3 of the inputer layer + the size of the output layer as my first hidden layer size. I then reduce this by half as my second layer. This is my general rule of thumb to take between 75% and 50% of the previous layer size.

class MLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy(MLPMiniBatch):
    def _cost(self, A, Y_enc, W):
        '''
        Get the objective function value
        Changes made:
            Made dynamic the A parameter to point to last layer
            Corrected l2 parameter signature to take in W instead of individual Ws
        '''
        cost = -np.mean(np.nan_to_num((Y_enc*np.log(A[-1])+(1-Y_enc)*np.log(1-A[-1]))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _cost(self, A_last, Y_enc, W):
        '''
        Get the objective function value
        Changes made:
            Need to pass through W as W can be dynamic 
            depending on size of network
            Renamed A3 to A_last for consistency
        '''
        cost = np.mean((Y_enc-A_last)**2)
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _get_gradient(self, A, Z, Y_enc, W):
        """ 
        Compute gradient step using backpropagation.
        Changes made:
            Changed V_last to be A[last layer] - Y_enc
        """
        # initialize master lists
        V = []
        grad_W = []
        grad_b = []
        
        # calculate the last layer V, W, b
        V_last = (A[-1] - Y_enc)
        gradW_last = V_last @ A[-2].T
        gradb_last = np.sum(V_last, axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
        
        # append last V, W, b
        V.append(V_last)
        grad_W.append(gradW_last)
        grad_b.append(gradb_last)
        
        # iterate through layers
        # need to reverse because it back propogates
        # also need to go from last layer to 1st layer (0 isn't a layer)
        for layer in reversed(range(1, self.n_layers)):
            V_idx = abs(layer - self.n_layers + 1)

            # update V
            V_layer = A[layer] * (1 - A[layer]) * (W[layer].T @ V[V_idx])
            V.append(V_layer)
            
            # update W
            gradW_layer = V[V_idx + 1] @ A[layer-1].T
            
            # regularize weights that are not bias terms
            gradW_layer += W[layer-1] * self.l2_C
            grad_W.insert(0, gradW_layer)
            
            # update b
            gradb_layer = np.sum(V[V_idx + 1], axis=1).reshape((-1,1))
            grad_b.insert(0, gradb_layer)

        return grad_W, grad_b

class MLPBetterInitial(MLPMiniBatchCrossEntropy):             
    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights Glorot and He normalization."""
        # initialize empty list to store all weights
        All_W = []
        
        # initialize empty list to store all bias
        All_b = []
        
        # initialize first layer weights with Glorot and He normalization
        init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden[0] + self.n_features_))
        W_first = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden[0], self.n_features_))

        # append to master W
        All_W.append(W_first)
        
        # initialize first layer bias
        b_first = np.zeros((self.n_hidden[0], 1))
        
        # append to master b
        All_b.append(b_first)
        
        # iterate through the layers
        for layer in range(self.n_layers - 2):  # Subtract 2 because we are skipping 1st and last layer
            
            # initialize hidden layer weights
            init_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6. / (self.n_hidden[layer + 1] + self.n_hidden[layer]))
            W_mid = np.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound,(self.n_hidden[layer + 1], self.n_hidden[layer]))
            All_W.append(W_mid)
            
            # initialize hidden layer bias
            b_mid = np.zeros((self.n_hidden[layer + 1], 1))
            All_b.append(b_mid)
        
        # reduce the final layer magnitude in order to balance the size of the gradients
        # between 
        last_bound = 4*np.sqrt(6 / (self.n_output_ + self.n_hidden[-1]))
        W_last = np.random.uniform(-last_bound, last_bound,(self.n_output_, self.n_hidden[-1]))
        
        # append to master W
        All_W.append(W_last)
        
        # finalize bias
        b_last = np.zeros((self.n_output_, 1))
        All_b.append(b_last)
        
        return All_W, All_b

Exceptional Work (1 points total) 5000 level student: You have free reign to provide additional analyses. One idea (required for 7000 level students): Implement adaptive momentum (AdaM) in the five layer neural network and quantify the performance.

I decided to implement all methods, including AdaM in the same block of code. I'm not trying to show off, it was just convenient to start with implementing AdaGrad and having the 3 other optimizers be just one more step of implementation per the previous optimzer (AdaGrad -> RMSProp -> AdaDelta -> AdaM). In fact, this way of implementing has taught me the real differences in the math, as opposed to reading TensorFlow documentation and guessing which one would be best for my model.

One thing I'd like to note is my implementation of V and M. The equation calls for a parameter called gamma. I used beta1 because of 2 ideas I found while researching: 1. gamma is typically 0.9, which beta1 is also typically 0.9, and 2. I've seen some documentations use beta as a term instead of gamma as the term. So, I'm not sure if beta1 is supposed to be used in place of gamma, but I did anyways. In a real production supported scenario, we would use gamma.

class MLPAdaptiveLearning(MLPBetterInitial):
    def __init__(self, beta1=0.9, beta2=0.999, epsilon=1e-8, optimizer="RMSProp", **kwds):

        # need to add to the original initializer 
        self.beta1 = beta1
        self.beta2 = beta2
        self.epsilon = epsilon
        self.optimizer = optimizer
        
        # but keep other keywords
        super().__init__(**kwds)
        
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        """ Learn weights from training data. With mini-batch"""
        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W, self.b = self._initialize_weights()

        # start momentum at zero for previous updates
        rho_W = []
        rho_W_prev = []
        rho_b = []
        rho_b_prev = []
        g = []
        g_prev = []
        v = []
        v_prev = []
        m = []
        m_prev = []
        m_hat = []
        v_hat = []
        
        # iterate through layers and initialize momentum
        for layer in range(self.n_layers):
            rho_W.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            rho_W_prev.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            rho_b.append(np.zeros(self.b[layer].shape))
            rho_b_prev.append(np.zeros(self.b[layer].shape))
            g.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            g_prev.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            v.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            v_prev.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            m.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            m_prev.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            m_hat.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))
            v_hat.append(np.zeros(self.W[layer].shape))

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []
        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
        # keep track of validation, if given
        # provide tuple of this
        # this tracks the health of validation
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            eta = self.eta / (1 + self.decrease_const*i)

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1)%print_progress==0:
                sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs))
                sys.stderr.flush()

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = np.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(range(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for j, idx in enumerate(mini):

                # feedforward - changed here because function changed in inherited class
                A, Z = self._feedforward(X_data[idx], self.W, self.b)
                
                # calculate cose - changed here because function changed above
                cost = self._cost(A[-1],Y_enc[:, idx], self.W)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                grad_W, grad_b = self._get_gradient(A=A, Z=Z, Y_enc=Y_enc[:, idx], W=self.W)
                
                # iterate through the network
                for layer in range(self.n_layers):

                    # update W based on optimizer
                    if self.optimizer == "AdaGrad":
                        
                        # momentum calculations AdaGrad
                        g[layer] = self.beta1 * g_prev[layer] + (grad_W[layer] ** 2) 
                        rho_W[layer] = 1/np.sqrt(g[layer] + self.epsilon) * grad_W[layer]
                        
                    if self.optimizer == "RMSProp":
                        
                        # momentum calculations RMSProp
                        g[layer] = (grad_W[layer] ** 2)
                        v[layer] = self.beta1 * v_prev[layer] + (1 - self.beta1) * g[layer]
                        rho_W[layer] = 1/np.sqrt(v[layer] + self.epsilon) * grad_W[layer]
                    
                    if self.optimizer == "AdaDelta":
                        
                        # momentum calculations AdaDelta
                        g[layer] = (grad_W[layer] ** 2)
                        v[layer] = self.beta1 * v_prev[layer] + (1 - self.beta1) * g[layer]
                        m[layer] = self.beta1 * m_prev[layer] + (1 - self.beta1) * grad_W[layer]
                        rho_W[layer] = 1/np.sqrt(v[layer] + self.epsilon) * m[layer]
                    
                    if self.optimizer == "AdaM":
                        # momentum calculations AdaM
                        g[layer] = (grad_W[layer] ** 2)
                        m[layer] = self.beta1 * m_prev[layer] + (1 - self.beta1) * grad_W[layer]
                        v[layer] = self.beta2 * v_prev[layer] + (1 - self.beta2) * g[layer]
                        m_hat[layer] = m[layer]/(1 - self.beta1**(layer+1))
                        v_hat[layer] = v[layer]/(1 - self.beta2**(layer+1))
                        rho_W[layer] = m_hat[layer]/np.sqrt(v_hat[layer] + self.epsilon)

                    # update bias momentum
                    rho_b[layer] = eta * grad_b[layer]
                    
                    # update weights and bias
                    self.W[layer] -= (eta * rho_W[layer])
                    self.b[layer] -= (rho_b[layer] + (self.alpha * rho_b_prev[layer]))
                    rho_W_prev[layer] = rho_W[layer]
                    rho_b_prev[layer] = rho_b[layer]
                    g_prev[layer] = g[layer]
                    v_prev[layer] = v[layer]
                    m_prev[layer] = m[layer]

            self.cost_.append(mini_cost)
            self.score_.append(accuracy_score(y_data,self.predict(X_data)))
            
            # calculate the validation accuracy
            if XY_test is not None:
                self.val_score_.append(accuracy_score(y_test,self.predict(X_test)))
            
        return self
